Removes the darwin install guard around `libghostty` install steps and
registers the shared lib in the artifact registry so downstream
`dep.artifact("ghostty")` lookups resolve on macOS.

Upstream `build.zig` only registers `b.addInstallLibFile` for non-darwin
targets, even though `GhosttyLib.initShared` / `initStatic` build the
library fine on darwin too. Without the install step, the artifact never
gets exposed via `dep.artifact("ghostty")` to downstream consumers like
djinn that want to embed the full surface API instead of the bare VT
parser.

A second issue surfaced once the guard was removed in the spike:
upstream's `lib_shared.install(name)` only adds an `addInstallLibFile`
step (a file install), but `Dependency.artifact()` walks the
`InstallArtifact` step registry ‚Äî populated only by `b.installArtifact`.
This patch additionally calls `b.installArtifact(<*Compile>)`, recovering
the underlying `*Compile` via `step.cast` so neither `GhosttyLib`'s
struct nor its install method need to change.

Upstream comment on the original guard ("we shouldn't have this guard
but we don't currently build on macOS this way ironically so we need to
fix that") confirms the gating is unintentional. PR'ing this fix
upstream needs domain understanding (xcframework + Xcode build path
interaction, plus whether `installArtifact` belongs in `GhosttyLib` or
the consumer side) the djinn maintainer hasn't acquired yet ‚Äî apply
locally for now.

Patch rev / pinned ghostty: 1.3.2-dev fdb6e3d2c8543e2e756b7e07f44372efbc0fba4b
Re-verify the patch context if the pin moves; the slice we're rewriting
is small enough that fuzz match should still apply, but the surrounding
`else if (!config.emit_lib_vt)` block could shift.

--- a/build.zig
+++ b/build.zig
@@ -170,18 +170,30 @@
         const lib_shared = try buildpkg.GhosttyLib.initShared(b, &deps);
         const lib_static = try buildpkg.GhosttyLib.initStatic(b, &deps);

-        // We shouldn't have this guard but we don't currently
-        // build on macOS this way ironically so we need to fix that.
-        if (!config.target.result.os.tag.isDarwin()) {
-            lib_shared.installHeader(); // Only need one header
-            if (config.target.result.os.tag == .windows) {
-                lib_shared.install("ghostty.dll");
-                lib_static.install("ghostty-static.lib");
-            } else {
-                lib_shared.install("libghostty.so");
-                lib_static.install("libghostty.a");
-            }
+        // djinn local patch: drop the darwin install guard and also
+        // register the shared lib via `b.installArtifact` so that
+        // downstream consumers can resolve it via `dep.artifact()`.
+        // Upstream's `lib_shared.install(name)` only adds an
+        // `addInstallLibFile` step (file install), which doesn't
+        // populate the `InstallArtifact` registry that
+        // `Dependency.artifact()` walks. Calling `installArtifact`
+        // on the underlying `*Compile` (recovered via `step.cast`)
+        // adds the missing registry entry without changing any of
+        // the existing install paths.
+        lib_shared.installHeader(); // Only need one header
+        if (config.target.result.os.tag == .windows) {
+            lib_shared.install("ghostty.dll");
+            lib_static.install("ghostty-static.lib");
+        } else if (config.target.result.os.tag.isDarwin()) {
+            lib_shared.install("libghostty.dylib");
+            lib_static.install("libghostty.a");
+        } else {
+            lib_shared.install("libghostty.so");
+            lib_static.install("libghostty.a");
         }
+        if (lib_shared.step.cast(std.Build.Step.Compile)) |c| {
+            b.installArtifact(c);
+        }
     }

     // macOS only artifacts. These will error if they're initialized for
